This is the beginning of a learning journey I am committing to publicly. I am studying cloud security from the ground up, sharing everything theory, notes, labs, and resources openly on my GitHub. The plan is to move through the foundational layers in order: Storage, Compute, Networking, Databases, Cloud Operations, Security, then Serverless. Every step gets documented and shared, and I am hoping to connect with enthusiasts and experts along the way who can sharpen the ideas as we go.Introduction to Storage in AWS (Cloud)Today kicks off with Storage, one of the most fundamental building blocks of cloud infrastructure. The focus areas for this module are the types of storage solutions available, the features and concepts of Amazon S3, S3 storage classes, hands-on work like creating buckets and uploading objects, S3 configuration for cost saving and security, other AWS storage solutions, and building a static website with S3. The journey through this topic goes: Intro to Storage, Intro to Amazon Simple Storage Service, Using Amazon S3, then Additional AWS Storage Services.On-Premises Storage vs Cloud StorageBefore diving into AWS specifics, it helps to understand what problem cloud storage is actually solving. In an on-premises setup, the server lives within your organisation's own infrastructure, physically onsite in many cases. The company is fully responsible for maintaining, controlling, and administering it. Data sharing happens over local networks, which keeps things fast internally but creates real limits around accessibility and scale.Cloud storage flips this model entirely. The cloud provider procures, installs, and maintains all the hardware, software, and supporting infrastructure inside its own data centres. You access everything over the internet with no physical server rooms and no on-site maintenance teams required. The benefits that come with this shift are significant: lower costs since you pay for what you use, strong built-in security, anywhere accessibility, easy scalability, and the peace of mind of managed backups.Types of Cloud StorageThere are three core types of cloud storage and understanding the difference between them is foundational to everything that follows.Block Storage breaks data into fixed-size blocks and stores each piece separately with a unique identifier. Because each block can be configured independently, different blocks can work with different operating systems. Think of it like a hard drive that has been sliced into equal-sized chunks, fast and flexible but tightly coupled to the system it is attached to.File Storage organises data in a hierarchical structure, folders within folders, and lets multiple users and applications access it through a shared file system. It is the cloud equivalent of the centralised shared network drives that corporate offices have used for decades. Familiar, structured, and great for collaboration.Object Storage is where Amazon S3 lives and it works differently from the other two. Every file is stored as a complete object with three parts: the data itself, metadata which is information about the data like object size and purpose, and an object key which is the unique identifier for that object. Crucially, updating a file in object storage means replacing the entire object rather than patching a piece of it like block storage does. This makes it ideal for large amounts of unstructured data like images, videos, backups, and logs.
